# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# ARCHITECTURE DECISIONS (record here as they're made)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
#
# Q: Where do chart filters (brush selections) attach in the tree?
# A: TBD — Recommendation: always at root level as direct children.
#    Chart filters are quick, visual interactions — nesting them would
#    be confusing. They show as regular leaves in the bar but originate
#    from chart interaction rather than manual creation.
#
# Q: External API — break or preserve backward compatibility?
# A: TBD — Recommendation: dual callbacks.
#    - onFilterChange (existing) emits flat SerializedFilter[] (compat)
#    - onFilterTreeChange (new) emits SerializedFilterTree
#    - initialFilters (existing) accepts flat array (auto-migrated to tree)
#    - initialFilterTree (new) accepts tree directly
#    Deprecate flat versions after consumers migrate.
#
# Q: Can a column appear in multiple leaves across different groups?
# A: TBD — Recommendation: Yes. Example: AGE > 18 in group 1, AGE < 65
#    in group 2. The setFilterForColumn() compat shim updates the first
#    match only. Tree-aware UI can manage multiple.
#
# Q: How does FilterRow (inline per-column inputs) work with tree?
# A: TBD — Recommendation: FilterRow continues to use the compat Map.
#    It represents "quick filter per column" and always targets the root
#    group. For multi-filter-per-column scenarios, use the FilterBar UI.
#
